response:
 Since the coin is fair, the probability of getting heads or tails on any single toss is {eq}\displaystyle \rm \frac{1}{2}

{/eq}. The i-th toss and j-th toss are independent events for any i and j.

Because there are two heads needed, only two tails are allowed.

For the sake of clarity, we distribute an r variables for the number of heads and s variables for the number of tails. i.e., r is the number of heads and s is the number of tails such that {eq}\displaystyle r + s = \rm 6

{/eq} thus, {eq}\displaystyle s = 6-r

{/eq} and {eq}\displaystyle x = 6

{/eq} since they all represent the number of trials


table


| Total heads | Total tails |
|---|---|
| s = 6 | r = 0 |
| s = 5 | r = 1 |
| s = 4 | r = 2 |
| s = 3 | r = 3 |
| s = 2 | r = 4 |
| s = 1 | r = 5 |
| s = 0 | r = 6 |


Now, we find the number of sequences for two heads among the 6-similarly listed columns:



{eq}\displaystyle \rm P(X = s) = ^x_{r} P{}^{6}{_6} (0.5)^{s} (1-0.5)^{x-s}

{/eq}

{eq}\displaystyle \rm P(X = s) = ^{6}_{0} P{}^{6}{_6}(0.5)^{0} (1-0.5)^{6-0}

{/eq}



{eq}\displaystyle \rm P(X = s) = ^{6}_{2} P{}^{6}{_6}(0.5)^{2} (1-0.5)^{6-2}

{/eq}



{eq}\displaystyle \rm P(X = s) = ^{6}_{3} P{}^{6}{_6}(0.5)^{3} (1-0.5)^{6-3}

{/eq}



{eq}\displaystyle \rm P(X = s) = ^{6}_{4} P{}^{6}{_6}(0.5)^{4} (1-0.5)^{6-4}

{/eq}



{eq}\displaystyle \rm P(X = s) = ^{6}_{5} P{}^{6}{_6}(0.5)^{5} (1-0.5)^{6-5}

{/eq}



{eq}\displaystyle \rm P(X = s) = ^{6}_{6} P{}^{6}{_6}(0.5)^{6} (1-0.5)^{6-6}

{/eq}



{eq}\displaystyle \rm P(X = s) = ^{6}_{0} P{}^{6}{_6}0.5^6 (1-0.5)^6+ ^{6}_{2} P{}^{6}{_6}0.5^2 (1-0.5)^6+ ^{6}_{3} P{}^{6}{_6}0.5^3 (1-0.5)^6+ ^{6}_{4} P{}^{6}{_6}0.5^4 (1-0.5)^6+ ^{6}_{5} P{}^{6}{_6}0.5^5 (1-0.5)^6+ ^{6}_{6} P{}^{6}{_6}0.5^6 (1-0.5)^6\\

\displaystyle \rm P(X = s) = \boxed{ \dfrac{5}{128}}

{/eq}

problem:
Piravena must make a trip from $A$ to $B$, then from $B$ to $C$, then from $C$ to $A$.  Each of these three parts of the trip is made entirely by bus or entirely by airplane.  The cities form a right-angled triangle as shown, with $C$ a distance of 3000 km from $A$ and with $B$ a distance of 3250 km from $A$. To take a bus, it costs Piravena $\$0.15$ per kilometer. To take an airplane, it costs her a $\$100$ booking fee, plus $\$0.10$ per kilometer. [asy]

pair A, B, C;

C=(0,0);

B=(0,1250);

A=(3000,0);

draw(A--B--C--A);

label("A", A, SE);

label("B", B, NW);

label("C", C, SW);

label("3000 km", (A+C)/2, S);

label("3250 km", (A+B)/2, NE);

draw((0,125)--(125,125)--(125,0));

[/asy]

Piravena chose the least expensive way to travel between cities.  What was the total cost?

